    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-11-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-11-13T19:00:00-05:00" n="520"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d520">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">818.014C/115: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hornibrook</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 13, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>63. Your despatch no. 938, October 30, 1939.<note n="4" xml:id="d520fn4">Not
                        printed.</note> There has been no change in the position of this Government
                    regarding the possible purchase of Cocos Island, as stated in the Department’s
                    instruction no. 34 of January 4, 1938.<note n="5" xml:id="d520fn5">
                        <ref target="frus1938v05#pg_467">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1938, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 467</ref>.</note> If the question of
                    purchase of the Island is again raised with you or any member of the Legation,
                    you should be guided accordingly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
